Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

**1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and add a custom toolbar item:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await TryNavigateBack())
        });
    }

    // Handles hardware/gesture back (Android back button, swipe)
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () => await TryNavigateBack());
            return true; // Cancel default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async Task TryNavigateBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and leave?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // User chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the arrow with "Cancel" text (iOS shows text; Android shows it depending on theme).
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` intercepts taps on the shell back button.
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` returning `true` cancels the Android hardware/gesture back.
- iOS swipe-back gesture isn't caught by either — disable it if needed:

```csharp
Shell.SetPresentationMode(this, PresentationMode.ModalAnimated);
// Or on iOS specifically:
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.NavigationExtensions... // platform-specific
```

To fully block iOS swipe-back, you can disable it in a custom handler or push the page modally instead.
